# Curse of dimensionality

#### Harsha Achyuthuni

#### 20/03/2020

## Multi dimension intuition

Because we are all used to two or three dimensions, we are not used to multidimensional thinking. In this blog, I want to show the curse of dimensionality using an example.

Take a classification problem, for example. In a classification problem, the goal is to define a distinct boundary between the classes. The probability of a data point to be of a particular class increases as it is farther away from the decision boundary. Pick a random point from a line of unit length. The probability of the point being in the edges (defined by <0.001 from the border) is

  
[ p = frac{2times 0.001}{1} = 0.002 = 2%]<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /> Similarly, in a two-dimensional space, consider a unit square. The probability of a point being in the edges is:  
[ p = 1- frac{area,of,square,of,0.998,side}{area,of,unit,square} = 1 &#8211; frac{0.998\*0.998}{1\*1} = 0.003996 = 4% ] 

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />  In a three dimensional space, in a unit cube, the probability of a point being in the edges is:

  
[ p = 1- frac{area,of,cube,of,0.998,length}{area,of,unit,cube}= 1 &#8211; frac{0.998times 0.998times 0.998}{1times1times1} = 0.005988008 = 5%] 

similarly, in an n-dimensional space, the probability would be: [ p = 1 &#8211; 0.998^n] As ‘n’ increases, the probability of a data point is on the edges (defined by <0.001 from the border) is:<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /> 

For just 50 dimensions, almost 10% of the data is on the edges. At 3000 dimensions, almost 99.75% of the data is on the edges.

In problems with a large number of features, a very high proportion of the data would be at the edges. This is called the curse of dimensionality and is the reason why feature engineering is essential. References:

  
1. [Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras, and TensorFlow &#8211; Aurélien Géron](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/hands-on-machine-learning/9781492032632/)
